Laura asked, with bright tears of happiness  gathering in Laura eyes.
"Even MY bewilderment has its limits," I replied.
"I think I can still answer  for knowing my own child."
"Child!"
Laura exclaimed, with all Laura easy gaiety of old times.
"Do you talk in  that familiar manner of one of the landed gentry of England?
Are you aware,  when I present this illustrious baby to your notice, in whose presence you  stand?
Evidently not!
Let me make two eminent personages known to one another:  Mr. Walter Hartright—THE HEIR OF LIMMERIDGE."
So Laura spoke.
In writing those last words, I have written all.
The pen falters  in my hand.
The long, happy labour of many months is over.
Marian was the good  angel of our lives—let Marian end our Story.
